Mensur fencing is such a high civilization technology. You get to duel someone, defend your honor - and yet he does not have to die, he gets to see a new day and a new sun. Blood is spilled, scars are left, mothers do not have to cry. Probably the clearest expression of "sports".

Dueling with swords, guns, etc. is honorable, beautiful, but brutal, barbaric. The church bans it for reason. This is fully resolved with Mensur, the academic style. You don't have to repeat Cain's big sin, but you still get to draw blood and leave your mark on his cheek. Cheers.
Even when it turned to recreation in its final days, the tradition to initiate bouts by a symbolic insult of one's honor was preserved, Evola talks about this

Baron Julius Evola mentions that even in its latter days when it turned to a mere recreational activity, Mensur kept the tradition of bouts being started with a symbolic insult on the other's honor that he is then prompted to defend, IIRC. Illustrative of its origins and meaning.
